built with pdoc

pdoc.markdown2

A fast and complete Python implementation of Markdown.

[from http://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/]

Markdown is a text-to-HTML filter; it translates an easy-to-read / easy-to-write structured text format into HTML. Markdown's text format is most similar to that of plain text email, and supports features such as headers, emphasis, code blocks, blockquotes, and links.

Markdown's syntax is designed not as a generic markup language, but specifically to serve as a front-end to (X)HTML. You can use span-level HTML tags anywhere in a Markdown document, and you can use block level HTML tags (like

and as well).

Module usage:

>>> import markdown2
>>> markdown2.markdown("*boo!*")  # or use `html = markdown_path(PATH)`
u'<p><em>boo!</em></p>\n'

>>> markdowner = Markdown()
>>> markdowner.convert("*boo!*")
u'<p><em>boo!</em></p>\n'
>>> markdowner.convert("**boom!**")
u'<p><strong>boom!</strong></p>\n'

This implementation of Markdown implements the full "core" syntax plus a number of extras (e.g., code syntax coloring, footnotes) as described on https://github.com/trentm/python-markdown2/wiki/Extras.

cmdln_desc = 'A fast and complete Python implementation of Markdown, a\ntext-to-HTML conversion tool for web writers.\n\nSupported extra syntax options (see -x|--extras option below and\nsee <https://github.com/trentm/python-markdown2/wiki/Extras> for details):\n\n* admonitions: Enable parsing of RST admonitions.\n* breaks: Control where hard breaks are inserted in the markdown.\n Options include:\n - on_newline: Replace single new line characters with <br> when True\n - on_backslash: Replace backslashes at the end of a line with <br>\n* break-on-newline: Alias for the on_newline option in the breaks extra.\n* code-friendly: Disable _ and __ for em and strong.\n* cuddled-lists: Allow lists to be cuddled to the preceding paragraph.\n* fenced-code-blocks: Allows a code block to not have to be indented\n by fencing it with \'```\' on a line before and after. Based on\n <http://github.github.com/github-flavored-markdown/> with support for\n syntax highlighting.\n* footnotes: Support footnotes as in use on daringfireball.net and\n implemented in other Markdown processors (tho not in Markdown.pl v1.0.1).\n* header-ids: Adds "id" attributes to headers. The id value is a slug of\n the header text.\n* highlightjs-lang: Allows specifying the language which used for syntax\n highlighting when using fenced-code-blocks and highlightjs.\n* html-classes: Takes a dict mapping html tag names (lowercase) to a\n string to use for a "class" tag attribute. Currently only supports "img",\n "table", "thead", "pre", "code", "ul" and "ol" tags. Add an issue if you require\n this for other tags.\n* link-patterns: Auto-link given regex patterns in text (e.g. bug number\n references, revision number references).\n* markdown-in-html: Allow the use of `markdown="1"` in a block HTML tag to\n have markdown processing be done on its contents. Similar to\n <http://michelf.com/projects/php-markdown/extra/#markdown-attr> but with\n some limitations.\n* metadata: Extract metadata from a leading \'---\'-fenced block.\n See <https://github.com/trentm/python-markdown2/issues/77> for details.\n* middle-word-em: Allows or disallows emphasis syntax in the middle of words,\n defaulting to allow. Disabling this means that `this_text_here` will not be\n converted to `this<em>text</em>here`.\n* nofollow: Add `rel="nofollow"` to add `<a>` tags with an href. See\n <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nofollow>.\n* numbering: Support of generic counters. Non standard extension to\n allow sequential numbering of figures, tables, equations, exhibits etc.\n* pyshell: Treats unindented Python interactive shell sessions as <code>\n blocks.\n* smarty-pants: Replaces \' and " with curly quotation marks or curly\n apostrophes. Replaces --, ---, ..., and . . . with en dashes, em dashes,\n and ellipses.\n* spoiler: A special kind of blockquote commonly hidden behind a\n click on SO. Syntax per <http://meta.stackexchange.com/a/72878>.\n* strike: text inside of double tilde is ~~strikethrough~~\n* tag-friendly: Requires atx style headers to have a space between the # and\n the header text. Useful for applications that require twitter style tags to\n pass through the parser.\n* tables: Tables using the same format as GFM\n <https://help.github.com/articles/github-flavored-markdown#tables> and\n PHP-Markdown Extra <https://michelf.ca/projects/php-markdown/extra/#table>.\n* toc: The returned HTML string gets a new "toc_html" attribute which is\n a Table of Contents for the document. (experimental)\n* use-file-vars: Look for an Emacs-style markdown-extras file variable to turn\n on Extras.\n* wiki-tables: Google Code Wiki-style tables. See\n <http://code.google.com/p/support/wiki/WikiSyntax#Tables>.\n* wavedrom: Support for generating Wavedrom digital timing diagrams\n* xml: Passes one-liner processing instructions and namespaced XML tags.\n'

def mark_stage(stage: Stage):

Decorator that handles executing relevant Extras before and after this Stage executes.

class Markdown:
Markdown( html4tags: bool = False, tab_width: int = 4, safe_mode: Optional[Literal['replace', 'escape']] = None, extras: Union[List[str], Dict[str, Any], NoneType] = None, link_patterns: Optional[collections.abc.Iterable[Tuple[re.Pattern, Union[str, Callable[[re.Match], str]]]]] = None, footnote_title: Optional[str] = None, footnote_return_symbol: Optional[str] = None, use_file_vars: bool = False, cli: bool = False)

stage: Stage

Current "stage" of markdown conversion taking place

order: float

Same as Stage but will be +/- 0.5 of the value of Stage. This allows extras to check if they are running before or after a particular stage with if md.order < md.stage.

@mark_stage(Stage.POSTPROCESS)
def postprocess(self, text: str) -> str:

A hook for subclasses to do some postprocessing of the html, if desired. This is called before unescaping of special chars and unhashing of raw HTML spans.

@mark_stage(Stage.PREPROCESS)
def preprocess(self, text: str) -> str:

A hook for subclasses to do some preprocessing of the Markdown, if desired. This is called after basic formatting of the text, but prior to any extras, safe mode, etc. processing.

def header_id_from_text(self, text: str, prefix: str, n: Optional[int] = None) -> str:

Generate a header id attribute value from the given header HTML content.

This is only called if the "header-ids" extra is enabled. Subclasses may override this for different header ids.

@param text {str} The text of the header tag @param prefix {str} The requested prefix for header ids. This is the value of the "header-ids" extra key, if any. Otherwise, None. @param n {int} (unused) The tag number, i.e. 1 for an

tag. @returns {str} The value for the header tag's "id" attribute. Return None to not have an id attribute and to exclude this header from the TOC (if the "toc" extra is specified).

class MarkdownWithExtras(Markdown):

A markdowner class that enables most extras:

  • footnotes
  • fenced-code-blocks (only highlights code if 'pygments' Python module on path)

These are not included:

  • pyshell (specific to Python-related documenting)
  • code-friendly (because it disables part of the syntax)
  • link-patterns (because you need to specify some actual link-patterns anyway)
extras = ['footnotes', 'fenced-code-blocks']

class Extra(abc.ABC):

Helper class that provides a standard way to create an ABC using inheritance.

Extra(md: Markdown, options: Optional[dict])

Args: md: An instance of Markdown options: a dict of settings to alter the extra's behaviour

name: str

An identifiable name that users can use to invoke the extra in the Markdown class

order: Tuple[Collection[Union[Stage, Type[Extra]]], Collection[Union[Stage, Type[Extra]]]]

Tuple of two iterables containing the stages/extras this extra will run before and after, respectively

md
options
@classmethod
def deregister(cls):

Removes the class from the extras registry and unsets its execution order.

@classmethod
def register(cls):

Registers the class for use with Markdown and calculates its execution order based on the order class attribute.

@abstractmethod
def run(self, text: str) -> str:

Run the extra against the given text.

Returns: The new text after being modified by the extra

def test(self, text: str) -> bool:

Check a section of markdown to see if this extra should be run upon it. The default implementation will always return True but it's recommended to override this behaviour to improve performance.

class ItalicAndBoldProcessor(Extra):

An ABC that provides hooks for dealing with italics and bold syntax. This class is set to trigger both before AND after the italics and bold stage. This allows any child classes to intercept instances of bold or italic syntax and change the output or hash it to prevent it from being processed.

After the I&B stage any hashes in the hash_tables instance variable are replaced.

name = 'italic-and-bold-processor'

An identifiable name that users can use to invoke the extra in the Markdown class

order = ((<Stage.ITALIC_AND_BOLD: 14>,), (<Stage.ITALIC_AND_BOLD: 14>,))

em_re = re.compile('(\\*|_)(?=\\S)(.*?\\S)\\1', re.DOTALL)

class MiddleWordEm(ItalicAndBoldProcessor):

Allows or disallows emphasis syntax in the middle of words, defaulting to allow. Disabling this means that this_text_here will not be converted to this<em>text</em>here.

MiddleWordEm(md: Markdown, options: Union[dict, bool])

Args: md: the markdown instance options: can be bool for backwards compatibility but will be converted to a dict in the constructor. All options are: - allowed (bool): whether to allow emphasis in the middle of a word. If options is a bool it will be placed under this key.
